# What is authentication

[[Cybersecurity/Bug Bounties/Authentication\|Authentication]] - the act of proving an assertion; the process of determining if an entity is who or what it claims to be.

### Login Example

A typical scenario for home banking authentication starts when an e-banking web application requests our ID, which could be a seven-digit number generated by the e-banking web application itself or a username chosen by the user. Then, on a second page, the application requests a password for the given ID. On a third page, the user must provide an OTP generated by a hardware token or received by SMS on their mobile phone. After providing the authentication details from the above two factors (2FA case), the e-banking web application checks if the ID, password, and OTP are valid.

## Overview of Attacks Against Authentication

There are three domains for authentication attacks:

* The **HAS** domain.
* The **IS** domain.
* The **KNOWS** domain.

### Attacking the HAS Domain

Even though hardware tokens must be possessed there are still potential attacks. Cloning a badge, breaking the crypto algorithm, or stealing the physical token.

A long range antenna can easily clone a classic NFC from 50 cm. That can lead to attacks where an attacker steals and clones a card by sitting next to a target.

### Attacking the IS Domain

Fingerprint readers, facial recognition, etc. all suffer from the problem that if their "something" is compromised then there is nothing they can do to change what they are. Fingerprints and facial patterns can be reproduced through Hi-def pictures.

### Attacking the KNOWS Domain

The knows domain is the simplest to understand and refers to things that the user knows.

## Default Credentials

Default credentials can often be used as humans are lazy. Default credentials are often used by maintainers working on Industrial Control Systems.

Some vendors of have hardcoded hidden accounts in there prodcuts. CWE 798 - Use of hard coded credentials is the CVE list for hardcoded creds.

There is a large [web database](https://www.cirt.net/passwords) that collects leaked default controls and [SecLists](https://github.com/danielmiessler/SecLists/blob/master/Passwords/Default-Credentials/default-passwords.csv)

## Weak Bruteforce Protections

There are many different security mechanisms designed to prevent automated attacks.  Things like CAPTCAH or Rate Limits.

### CAPTCHA
#captcha

CAPTCHA is an acronym: Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans apart. Sometimes there is weak implementation of captcha like when the imgid take contains the answer to the captcha.

Developers should not try and implement captcha on their own but instead should rely on tried and tested captcha and make it required after very few failed logins.

### Rate limiting

Having a counter that increments after each failed attempt, an application can block a user after three failed attempts within 60 seconds and notify the user accordingly.

After being blocked for rate limiting there may be an account lockout that requires a manual reset. The site developer will need to measure the inconvenience of brute forcing protection to the user and the protection provided.

## Insufficient Protections

Some of the precautions taken to increase security can be bypasssed if they are stored in areas where the attacker can tamper with them. For example, the User-Agent header can be changed easily.  The **X-Forwarded-For** header are used by some internet provdiers, mobile carriers, or big corporations to guess the actual source IP address.

## Brute Forcing Usernames
#BruteForce 

**Username Enumeration** is overlooked but important. Users often (always?) reuse usernames. Many web applications allow us to identify usernames, so we should take advantage of this functionality and use them for later attacks.

HTB uses **userid** and **username** so the function to find users by their name cannot be exploited.

Usernames are almost always less complicated than passwords. Having valid usernames makes brute force attacks much easier.

### User Unknown Attack
Anything that gives you feedback on whether an username is valid (i.e., "User unknown") can be used for username enumeration.

General attack:
* Find the string that reports that a user is "unknown" (e.g., "Uknown username, ").
* Fuzz the web page with a list of top usernames and a static dummy password.

We notice that an application returns Unknown Username.  So we fuzz the page with a top usernames list and a dummy password. (--hs paramater for the return string we're looking for.)

```shell
user@computer[/htb]$ wfuzz -c -z file,/opt/useful/SecLists/Usernames/top-usernames-shortlist.txt -d "Username=FUZZ&Password=dummypass" --hs "Unknown username" http://brokenauthentication.hackthebox.eu/user_unknown.php

********************************************************
* Wfuzz 3.1.0 - The Web Fuzzer                         *
********************************************************

Target: http://brokenauthentication.hackthebox.eu/user_unknown.php
Total requests: 17

===================================================================
ID           Response   Lines    Word     Chars       Payload
===================================================================

000000002:   200        56 L     143 W    1984 Ch     "admin"

Total time: 0.017432
Processed Requests: 17
Filtered Requests: 16
Requests/sec.: 975.1927
```

Here, wfuzz has hs hidden any string that contains "Unknown username"

The application should respond with "Invalid Credentials"

## Username Existence inference

At times you will be able to infer that a username is correct when the server provides some sort of hints like when it will pre-fill in a username for you.

## Timing Attack

The server may reveal the existence of a username by the amount of time it takes to respond to the  username password attempt.  This might be because the backend is programmed to, for example, check the username and then check the password hash if the username query returns true (i.e., the user exists) but just return false if the username exists. Thus, you can tell when a user exists becase the server will take longer to respond to requests that include a valid username.  This can be seen in the if($result) part of the code in the following php auth code:
```php
<?php
// connect to database
$db = mysqli_connect("localhost", "dbuser", "dbpass", "dbname");

// retrieve row data for user
$result = $db->query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE username="'.safesql($_POST['user']).'" AND active=1');

// $db->query() replies True if there are at least a row (so a user), and False if there are no rows (so no users)
if ($result) {
  // retrieve a row. don't use this code if multiple rows are expected
  $row = mysqli_fetch_row($result);

  // hash password using custom algorithm
  $cpass = hash_password($_POST['password']);
  
  // check if received password matches with one stored in the database
  if ($cpass === $row['cpassword']) {
	echo "Welcome $row['username']";
  } else {
    echo "Invalid credentials.";
  } 
} else {
  echo "Invalid credentials.";
}
?>
```
A better approach would have similar return times for valid and invalid usernames. The additional cpu load from mistyped user, etc, the overall cpu cost of strong v. weak hasing algorithms.

### Enumerate through Pasword Reset

Reset forms are often less protected than login forms. They leak information via the message "You should receive an email" v. "Username unknown." This is an easy attack vector, but noisy because valid users will get an email.

### Enumerate through registration Form

Registration forms usually tell if a username exists already. An attacker can register common usernames like, admin, administratoer, etc. to see if they exist. 

### Predictable usernames

May exist. There may be a user1000 or user 1001 account.  Admin may have accounts like "support.it"

## Brute Forcing Passwords

Once user names are discovered, password enumeration is just a step away.

### Password Issues

Users choose poor passwords if allowed to. Rotational requirements maket this worse and many users use the same passwords accross a variety of websites or applications.

### Policy Inference

Once you know the password policy, you can filter your guesses to meat the minimum password requirements. On almost all applications it can be possible to discover the requirements mby registering a new user.

Sometimes the application will respond with **Password does not meet complexity requirements** at first, but then give the requirements after several failures.

Register multiple passwords to try and discover the policy:
![Pasted image 20230212140203.png](data:image/png;base64,)

We now take a giant wordlist and extract only passwords that match this policy. Unix `grep` is not the fastest tool but allows us to do the job quickly using POSIX regular expressions. The command below will work against rockyou-50.txt, a subset of the well-known `rockyou` password leak present in SecLists. This command finds lines have at least one uppercase character (`'[[:upper:]]'`), and then only lines that also have a lowercase one (`'[[:lower:]]'`) and with a length of 8 and 12 chars ('^.{8,12}$') using extended regular expressions (-E).

```bash
user@computer $ grep '[[:upper:]]' rockyou.txt | grep '[[:lower:]]' | grep -E '^.{8,12}$'

416712
```
## Predictable Reset Token

Reset tokens are secret pieces of data generated by the application when a pasword reset token is requested. This allows us to reset the password without knwoing the password.
![Pasted image 20230212153746.png](data:image/png;base64,)
If the application allows the user to reset their password by URL or temp password sent by mail it should be a robust token generation function.

### Weak Token Generation
The token should be purely random. If reversibly encoded, you don't want a captured token to be reversed.

### Short Tokens
Tokens are sent vial email mainly and embedded. They should be long or they can be bruteforced.

### Weak Cryptography
Use modern, well-known tested crypto to generate tokens. Generation of your 'own crypto' leads to weak crypto.

### Reset Token as Temp Passsword.

When a password reset token is used, there is a decent to higher cahnce that the temporary passwords are being generated using a predictable algorithm like mt_rand(), md5(username), etc.  So test the security by analyzing captured tokens.

The [[Cybersecurity/Bug Bounties/Insufficient Entropy for Random Values\|Insufficient Entropy for Random Values]] page pertains to the use of mt_rand for token generation and how to break it.

### Authentication Credentials Handling

When users forget passwords, they can:
1. Request a new one sent by email.
2. Request a URL that will get them a new one.
3. Answer prefiled questions as proof of idnetiy.

### Guessable Answers
Basically guessable answers will be guessed.

### Username Injection
When a password change function does not check for authorization but rather is coded something like this:
```php
<?php
  if isset($_REQUEST['userid']) {
	$userid = $_REQUEST['userid'];
  } else if isset($_SESSION['userid']) {
	$userid = $_SESSION['userid'];
  } else {
	die("unknown userid");
  }
```
where a specific userid overrides the session suerid, then it is vulenerable to username injection.  Basically, intercept the request and then 

## Brute Forcing Cookies
Cookies used to contain much more data, but now the man concern is security so cookies serve as a unique identified that refers to a **session** store on the server-side.  Session cookies are used to discriminate bettween users.

There are other ways, like **HTTP Authentication** or an in-page security token such as the kind used by [ViewState](https://www.w3big.com/aspnet/aspnet-viewstate.html). 

### Cookie token tampering
Like password reset tokens, cookie tokens need to be generated; they are often generated based on guessable information. It is not rare to see tokens generated from important values like userid, grants, time, etc.

There's really no reason for this since everything could be handled server-side.

An example of this is a ascii value coded as hex that includes userid and role.  We ca try things like changing the role in the ascii value and then encode to hex and see if that upgrades privilkeges.

Often web applications encode tokens. For example, some encoding algorithms, such as hex encoding and base64, can be recognized by a trained eye just by having a quick look at the token itself. Others are more tricky. A token could be somehow transformed using, for example, XOR or compression functions before being encoded. We suggest always checking for magic bytes when you have a sequence of bytes that looks like junk to you since they can help you identify the format. Wikipedia has a list of common [file signatures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_file_signatures) to help us with the above.

[Decodify](https://github.com/s0md3v/Decodify) is a tool that can help with decode guessing. Also, [Dencode](https://dencode.com/en).

Base 64 Alphabet:  A-Za-z0-9+/=  (i.e., if you see just these it may be b64 encoded.)
Hex: a-f and 0-9
URL: Will use percent encoding in place of reserved characters

[Cipher Identifier and analyzer](https://www.boxentriq.com/code-breaking/cipher-identifier#hexadecimal-code)


### Remember me token
A rememberme token is a session cookie that lasts for a longer time than usual. Often 7 days to a month. Moste attacks that are used against password reset tokens and generic cookies can be mounted against rememberme tokens.

### Encrypted or encoded token.
Cookies can contain the result of the encryption of a sequence of data. A weak crypto algorithm will lead to privilege escalation or authentication bypass, just like plain encoding could.

Web apps often encode tokens through hex encoding or through base64.

Something like [Cyberchef](https://gchq.github.io/CyberChef/) can be used to play a round with encoded strings to try and see how they were encoded. Other clues like the [[Cybersecurity/Bug Bounties/Magic Bytes\|magic bytes]] remain after encode.

Base64 is often used when there is a requirement to move date to and from a web application.

Sometimes the cookie is also set with random or pseudo-random values so an easy decode won't always lead toa successful attack.

## Insecure Token Handling

Tokens are different from cookies in that tokens are explicitly used to send authorization data. When we use token-based authorization, we receive an ID token from a trusted authority. This is often referred to as JSON Web token and token-based authorization.

### Token Lifetime

Tokens should expire after the user has been inactive for a given amount of time. And should also expire even if there is activity after a given amount of time. If it never expires, then the Session Fixation attack can be done.

### Session Fixation

A very important rule is that cookie tokens should expire as soon as the access level changes. This occurs when a  user is phised with a link taht has a fixed session value that is unkown to the web application. the web app should bounce the user, but when the user logs in the sessionid remains the same and te attacker can reuse it.

### Token in URL

In the past, tokens could be found in URLs when browsers would refer beause theye would refer with the whole URL in it. Modern browser strip this data. If we can get to web server logs we may be able to obtain many valid tokens. This is covered in [[Cybersecurity/Bug Bounties/File Inclusion\|File Inclusion]]

### Session Security

Secure session handling starts from giving the client user as little information as possible. Cookies shold be only a random sequence. The web application should hold the details. Session security should also cover multiple logins for the same user and concurrent usage of the same session token from different endpoints.

### Cookie Security

Cookies security should always be checked since cookies are used to send and receive tokens. They should be set as httponly and secure.
